    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-08-12T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-08-12T01:00:00-05:00" n="415"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d415">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/9304: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-08-12T14:00:00+08:00"
                            >August 12, 1937—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 12—8 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>453. A large number of Japanese cruiser[s] and destroyers has now assembled in
                    Shanghai harbor. Japanese airplane carrier reported to be off the coast in
                    Chusan Island area. Also reported but not definitely confirmed that two Japanese
                    transports with troops are approaching the mouth of the Yangtze. Japanese are
                    converting Japanese golf course immediately outside eastern boundary of the
                    Settlement as a landing field for aircraft.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>In discussions last evening between Japanese Consul General and Mayor, the
                        former asked for withdrawal of Peace Preservation Corps. A Japanese consular
                        officer confirms this but insists there <pb facs="0387" n="380"
                            xml:id="pg_380"/> was no ultimatum or time limit. The Mayor did not
                        agree and is presumably referring [to his Government?] for
                        instructions.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>There has been confirmed reports this morning of intensive preparation by
                        Peace Preservation Corps in the area near Shanghai. Situation very
                        tense.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Repeated to Nanking and Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
